Grammar seems off
How exactly? Not a native speaker but as someone who's spoken English most my life this doesn't ring any alarm bells.

Firstly, `AntisymmRel r` is a relation but `AntisymmRel r a b` is a proposition. Secondly, I would say "`r a b` and `r b a` both **hold**". ~~Thirdly (not your fault), antisymmetrization is an operation/function, and `AntisymmRel r` should probably be called the antisymmetriz**ed** relation rather than the antisymmetrization relation.~~

I suggest that you keep it simple:
```suggestion
/-- The antisymmetrization relation `AntisymmRel r` is defined so that `AntisymmRel r a b â†” r a b âˆ§ r b a`. -/
```
If you want to describe it with words, I'd say "`AntisymmRel r` is the conjunction of `r` with its flip".

Sorry, scratch the third part. `AntisymmRel r` is not the antisymmetrized relation since it's not antisymmetric. It's the equivalence relation to take quotient by to get the Antisymmetrization, so "antisymmetrization relation" is a proper / correct name.
`rw [AntisymmRel` already does this, so we don't need it

```suggestion
  trans _ _ _ := .trans
```

```suggestion
    AntisymmRel (Â· â‰¤ Â·) a c â†” AntisymmRel (Â· â‰¤ Â·) b d := by
```
Do we really want these lemmas? They are all consequences of symmetry and transitivity of `AntisymmRel (Â· â‰¤ Â·)`.
All of them are encoding an important fact: all of the order relations are preserved up to order equivalence.
IMO they should be stated with `AntisymmRel (Â· â‰¤ Â·)` replaced by `r` satisfying `IsSymm _ r` and `IsTrans _ r` and moved to that file.

This is *just* for the `antisymmRel_congr` lemmas, right? Otherwise I think they'd be false: `a â‰¤ b` does not imply `a â‰¤ c â†” b â‰¤ c`.

Do you have any file in mind?

Yeah, the three lemmas are what I commented on. Is it not showing as such?
![image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/d4bf00da-bfc3-4e81-b2dd-dd169c7a4b48)

The file where IsSymm and IsTrans are defined is Mathlib.Order.Defs.Unbundled.
I've added the generalizations, but kept the specialized `antisymmRel_congr` lemmas for discoverability.

```suggestion
theorem antisymmRel_comm : AntisymmRel r a b â†” AntisymmRel r b a :=
```
Can you move this to just before the `Preorder` section?

```suggestion
theorem le_iff_lt_or_antisymmRel : a â‰¤ b â†” a < b âˆ¨ AntisymmRel (Â· â‰¤ Â·) a b := by
  rw [lt_iff_le_not_le, AntisymmRel]
  tauto

@[trans]
theorem le_of_le_of_antisymmRel (hâ‚ : a â‰¤ b) (hâ‚‚ : AntisymmRel (Â· â‰¤ Â·) b c) : a â‰¤ c :=
  hâ‚.trans hâ‚‚.le

@[trans]
theorem le_of_antisymmRel_of_le (hâ‚ : AntisymmRel (Â· â‰¤ Â·) a b) (hâ‚‚ : b â‰¤ c) : a â‰¤ c :=
  hâ‚.le.trans hâ‚‚

@[trans]
theorem lt_of_lt_of_antisymmRel (hâ‚ : a < b) (hâ‚‚ : AntisymmRel (Â· â‰¤ Â·) b c) : a < c :=
  hâ‚.trans_le hâ‚‚.le

@[trans]
theorem lt_of_antisymmRel_of_lt (hâ‚ : AntisymmRel (Â· â‰¤ Â·) a b) (hâ‚‚ : b < c) : a < c :=
  hâ‚.le.trans_lt hâ‚‚

alias âŸ¨LE.le.lt_or_antisymmRel, _âŸ© := le_iff_lt_or_antisymmRel
alias LE.le.trans_antisymmRel := le_of_le_of_antisymmRel
alias AntisymmRel.trans_le := le_of_antisymmRel_of_le
alias LT.lt.trans_antisymmRel := lt_of_lt_of_antisymmRel
alias AntisymmRel.trans_lt := lt_of_antisymmRel_of_lt

instance : @Trans Î± Î± Î± (Â· â‰¤ Â·) (AntisymmRel (Â· â‰¤ Â·)) (Â· â‰¤ Â·) where
  trans := le_of_le_of_antisymmRel

instance : @Trans Î± Î± Î± (AntisymmRel (Â· â‰¤ Â·)) (Â· â‰¤ Â·) (Â· â‰¤ Â·) where
  trans := le_of_antisymmRel_of_le

instance : @Trans Î± Î± Î± (Â· < Â·) (AntisymmRel (Â· â‰¤ Â·)) (Â· < Â·) where
  trans := lt_of_lt_of_antisymmRel

instance : @Trans Î± Î± Î± (AntisymmRel (Â· â‰¤ Â·)) (Â· < Â·) (Â· < Â·) where
  trans := lt_of_antisymmRel_of_lt
```
is the style we use in `Order.Basic`

```suggestion
  âŸ¨refl _, refl _âŸ©

variable {r} in
lemma AntisymmRel.rfl [IsRefl Î± r] (a : Î±) : AntisymmRel r a a := antisymmRel_refl ..
```
The docstring reads like there are two relations. Can you clarify?
I'm not really sure how to write this better. I think I'll just remove the comment, since this statement isn't particularly hard to read.
